2026-06-18 19:53:27,551 - [_base_client] - [openai._base_client]: DEBUG - Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/chat/completions', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-723285f8-c628-41d1-bce2-0531a72d3be8', 'security': {'bearer_auth': True}, 'content': None, 'json_data': {'messages': [{'content': 'You are an expert research information synthesis agent. You summarize/answer retrieved research information into the most suscinct text possible, but without any extreme terseness that would lose any points, facts, or key information from the provided text you are asked to summarize.', 'role': 'system'}, {'content': "The following text chunks have been retrieved via web search from the reserach query:\n quality of life expats Hong Kong Singapore ranking\nSummarize the results, weighing importance by the relevancy score given, of the query (or provide an answer if the query is a question) with the retrieved results:\n\nResult number 0, relevance score: 0.82761955\nChinese background. Singapore's diversity is often seen as more welcoming with official policies celebrating multiculturalism. Hong Kong, while vibrant, has experienced more political and social challenges over the last few years affecting expat confidence. Part three, quality of life and living conditions. Quality of life is a huge factor when choosing where to live. In terms of safety, Singapore consistently ranks as one of the safest cities globally. Hong Kong is still very safe, but recent protests have raised concerns. When it comes to housing, Singapore's rental prices have increased sharply with a median rental for a one-bedroom apartment now around $2,500 to $3,500 a month. Hong Kong remains one of the most expensive places for housing with small flats averaging $3,000 to $4,000 [...] to rank higher in global competitiveness and ease of doing business, but Hong Kong still dominates sectors like finance, especially with its strong ties to mainland China. GDP per capita 2025 Singapore $88,000, Hong Kong $52,000. For job seekers, Singapore offers a broader base, finance, tech, biotech, education, and logistics, whereas Hong Kong remains financeheavy. Part two, demographics and diversity. Singapore's population is around 5.9 million with nearly 30% being expats. The population comprises of Chinese 74.3%, Malay 13.5%, Indian 9.0%, others 3.2%. Hong Kong's population has declined slightly to 7.2 million with about 9% expatriots. Hong Kong's population is predominantly Chinese with approximately 90% of people from a Chinese background. Singapore's diversity is often seen as [...] for housing with small flats averaging $3,000 to $4,000 monthly. Median rent for onebedroom in the city center. Singapore $2,500 to 3,500. Hong Kong $3,000 to $4,000. For transport, both cities excel. Singapore's MRT is cheaper and arguably more modern, while Hong Kong's MTR is extensive but aging slightly. Part four, lifestyle for singles, couples, and families. So, how does life differ based on your situation? If you're young and single, Hong Kong still boasts an unbeatable nightife and vibrant social scene. Singapore offers a more work hard, play moderately vibe, but has an amazing food and arts culture growing fast. Couples might lean towards Singapore for a better work life balance, easier immigration rules, and slightly more personal space. For families, Singapore may have the edge.\n\nResult number 1, relevance score: 0.7917732\nDay-to-day costs are largely comparable. Midrange restaurant meals: USD 15–25 per person; milk ~USD 3/liter; a dozen eggs ~USD 4. International school fees are heavy in both cities: USD 20,000–35,000 in Singapore and USD 18,000–38,000 in Hong Kong, with top-tier schools at the premium end. Healthcare is excellent in both hubs; many expats choose private insurance at ~USD 200–400/month.\n\nTaxes change the final math. Singapore applies progressive income tax up to 24%, plus a 9% Goods and Services Tax. Hong Kong’s territorial tax system caps personal rates at 17% (progressive) or 15% (standard), with no sales tax. On a USD 150,000 salary, Hong Kong typically leaves USD 10,000–15,000 more in your pocket than Singapore.\n\nSingapore vs Hong Kong Expats\n\nSingapore vs Hong Kong Expats [...] Logo\nLogo\nLogo\nLogo\n\n# Singapore vs Hong Kong Expats: A Comprehensive Guide to Costs, Jobs, and Quality of Life in 2026\n\nBenjamin Collins\n\n## Singapore vs Hong Kong Expats: Costs, Jobs, and Quality of Life in 2026\n\nTwo world-class cities. Two very different rhythms. When you weigh Singapore against Hong Kong as an expat destination, you’re choosing between efficiency and edge, tropical calm and vertical thrill. Singapore greets you with clean streets, lush parks, and family-friendly infrastructure. Hong Kong pulses with density, skyline drama, and a direct gateway to mainland China.\n\nFor most professionals, the decision comes down to three pillars that shape real daily life:\n\n“Choose the city that pays you not just in money, but in energy, time, and possibility.” [...] Utilities and transport flip some assumptions. Hong Kong electricity bills for a family flat hover near USD 120/month vs. Singapore’s ~USD 180 (air-con loads matter). Both metros are superb, with ~USD 100/month getting you essentially unlimited rides. Owning a car? In Singapore, the Certificate of Entitlement alone can add USD 80,000–100,000 before you buy the vehicle; Hong Kong’s limited parking and high registration fees also discourage ownership.\n\nResult number 2, relevance score: 0.769098\nIn the 2024 Expat City Ranking, Hong Kong gains 12 spots from its position in 2023 to rank 22nd out of 53 cities — continuing to improve since 2022 when it was in the bottom 10 (46th). Expats are also happier with their lives abroad, going from dead last in 2022 (50th) to 12th in 2024. Most indices are faring better, with the best-performing index being Personal Finance (19th). The same cannot be said for Working Abroad (46th).\n\n## Transit Options Improve & the Cuisine Delights\n\nQuality of Life in Hong Kong lands in an average 23rd place, as its five subcategories appear on opposite sides of the ranking — from Travel & Transit in the top 10 to Safety & Security in the bottom 10. [...] ## A Tale of Two Extremes\n\nIn terms of Expat Essentials, Hong Kong ranks 22nd. Among the mediocre performances of Digital Life (32nd) and Language (36th), Admin Topics (9th) stands out.\n\nMore than seven in ten expats are pleased with the availability of government services online (74% vs. 58% globally) and high-speed internet access at home (87% vs. 78%). However, their access to online services like social media (45th) is more restricted: 12% rate this factor negatively, double the global average of 6%.\n\nOn the bright side, it’s easy to deal with the local bureaucracy/authorities (8th) and obtain a visa to move to Hong Kong (5th) — only 3% of respondents found the visa process difficult (vs. 26% globally). [...] Expats feel safe in Hong Kong (9th) but rank political stability (50th) and the freedom to openly express themselves and their opinions (51st) in the bottom 10.\n\n## International Friend Circles\n\nThe Ease of Settling In Index is in 21st place. The majority of expats has a personal support network (10th) and is happy with their social life in Hong Kong (10th) — landing Finding Friends in 11th place. However, they don’t feel similarly about Local Friendliness (31st).\n\nIndeed, only 4% of respondents say they’re friends with mostly local residents (vs. 17% globally). The vast majority describes their friend groups as mixed (54% vs. 46% globally) or consisting of other expats (42% vs. 37%).\n\nResult number 3, relevance score: 0.5993685\nBesides housing I have found everything else to be way cheaper than the USA. Grabbing a quick work lunch is usually like $4-6 USD, groceries I spend ~$100 USD a week for three adults and 2 kids (we have a live in helper).\n\nI have only visited HK so I can't really compare but I find Singapore extremely livable and see myself being quite happy here for awhile.\n\n Reply  Share \n\n3 more replies \n\n3 more replies \n\n3 more replies\n\n10 more replies \n\n10 more replies \n\n10 more replies\n\n but yes it is true that singapore is pretty backwards in terms of lgbtq legislation\n\n2 more replies \n\n2 more replies \n\n2 more replies\n\nMore replies\n\n\n\n3 more replies \n\n3 more replies \n\n3 more replies\n\n13 more replies \n\n13 more replies \n\n13 more replies\n\nImage 13: u/explosivekyushu avatar\n\nexplosivekyushu\n\n•3y ago [...] Life in HK is only different for local families who have no path to living anywhere else and have to deal with the idea of sending their kids to local schools where national security and curriculum censorship is absolutely rife. Expats in Hong Kong have, for better or for worse, always lived a completely separate existence and that has not changed. Life is almost exactly as it was before. It's still very vibrant and exciting. You can still get permanent residence after 7 years with no effort. I love hiking and it is absolutely world class in Hong Kong. I work in Central, in the absolute thick of the city, and within half an hour I can be halfway up a jungle mountain or on a deserted beach. There's nowhere else I've ever been where that's remotely possible. [...] 2 more replies \n\n2 more replies\n\n[deleted]\n\n•3y ago\n\nI think HK got more green parks,mountains,islands and lovely beaches. It’s slightly bigger. I found Singapore a bit more chill than HK and more children friendly.\n\nImage 18: u/manki1113 avatar\n\nmanki1113\n\n•3y ago\n\nI think it really depends on what you’re looking for and what you need. I’m born and raised in HK, travelled for work but never lived in Singapore.\n\n1.   Hong Kong still gets hot in summer, but we do have winter unlike Singapore it’s pretty much summer throughout the year.\n\nResult number 4, relevance score: 0.5325473\n# Cost of Living City Ranking 2024\n\nAccording to Mercer’s 2024 cost-of-living data, Hong Kong, Singapore and Zurich are currently the costliest cities for international workers.\n\nThese three cities have kept the same positions in Mercer’s rankings that they had last year. At the other end of the spectrum, the cities that ranked the lowest for living costs are Islamabad, Lagos and Abuja.\n\nA number of key factors have influenced the world’s economy in recent years. In 2024, these factors continue to have an impact on the cost of living in major cities. [...] Inflation and exchange-rate fluctuations are directly affecting the pay and savings of internationally mobile employees (or those executing an international assignment).\n Heightened economic and geopolitical volatility, as well as local conflicts and emergencies, have led to additional expenses in areas such as housing, utilities, local taxes and education.\n In the case of the higher-ranking cities (Hong Kong, Singapore and Zurich), factors such as expensive housing markets, high transportation costs and higher cost of goods and services have all contributed to high living costs.\n Conversely, in Islamabad, Lagos and Abuja the demonstrably lower costs of living of international assignees have, in part, been driven by currency depreciations. [...] ## Regional overview\n\nOf the 10 most expensive cities for international assignees, half are located in Western Europe, with Switzerland being home to four. However, it is Southeast Asian cities that lead the list, with Hong Kong and Singapore remaining in the first and second positions, respectively. The two most affordable cities are Lagos (225) and Abuja (226), both located in Nigeria (on the African continent).\n\nEuropean cities feature heavily in the top 10 most expensive places to live. In addition to the four Swiss cities, London has joined the top 10 ranking in 8th place. Other expensive cities in the region include Copenhagen (11), Vienna (24), Paris (29) and Amsterdam (30).\n\n", 'role': 'user'}], 'model': 'MiniMaxAI/MiniMax-M2.7', 'max_tokens': 8192, 'stream': True}}
