, Hong Kong and Singapore top the list for cost of living. A family of four can expect to spend an estimated $9,000 a month to live in one of these cities, according to Numbeo, an online database of user-contributed information.\n\nAs global financial hubs, Singapore and Hong Kong attract expats from around the world, which can drive prices up, according to a report from HR consultancy Mercer in June.\n\nResult number 1, relevance score: 0.81524754\nis at USD$3,878 per month. Looking at this budget is not exactly a super high   life budget, I would say it's a middle working income person's budget, a working foreigner and   of course accommodation is the most expensive at HKD12,700 that's definitely without a doubt because   of scarcity of land. Food and groceries is not cheap as well and if you want your wants like entertainment, your different attractions and shopping as well, it is definitely not cheap so USD3878   will get you a kind of a middle class income kind of experience and if you compare with other cost   of living videos that we have done for you whether it's in Singapore, in Malaysia, in Thailand, in   Indonesia even in South Korea, Hong Kong actually is higher than the others. We're looking at around the   same middle [...] The household utilities, electricity, water will be   shared so that's $600 Hong Kong dollars, internet at 500 MBPs of course, you can go higher, I'm putting   at 600 divided by two $300 Hong Kong dollar, of course it can be higher as well. Handphone bill   as well $200 Hong Kong dollars, can be lower it can be higher as well, this is an estimate and   the household items that you share with your other half 1200 HKD divided by 2 = 600 and this works out to be   a total for the accommodation category at HKD12,700 per month at USD1628 for this working expat. As this   budget includes the total monthly living expenses of the working expat so this includes basic needs and   wants as well. This is the wants category which are included short trips to China and Macau because   they're just next [...] go home to sleep but they don't really spend a lot of time there because   everything's very small, very crammed unless you're very wealthy and you can stay in a three, four   bedroom condominium. Although, people rather spend their time outside you know where they can   eat, they can meet their boyfriend, their girlfriend, their partners, they can take a stroll, they can go   shopping and then they go home to rest. There are around 360,000 expats living and working here in   Hong Kong and their annual package is around 220k - 250,000 USD per annum. That's a lot, isn't it? However   a large chunk of it goes to the cost of living especially the rental. The higher pay package is   very tempting to increase your standard of living and why not? Hong Kong is such a metropolitan   city with\n\nResult number 2, relevance score: 0.7253574\nThe good news is that skilled workers can expect to earn a good salary, which makes the cost of living in Singapore more manageable. In 2024, the average salary for a mid level manager working in Singapore was around SGD$9,490/US$7,000 per month.\n\nOn top of this, tax rates in Singapore are very lenient and capped at 22%, so you will get to keep much more of your pay than you would in other countries.\n\nThe tax rates in Singapore in 2022 are as follows:\n\nGross income (SGD)\n\nTax rate\n\nAltogether, the GDP per capita for people living in Singapore was US$72,794 in 2021, putting it slightly ahead of the USA at US$70,248.\n\nResult number 3, relevance score: 0.72325134\n### pay 22.8% more for housing\n\n|  | Hong Kong | Singapore |  |\n ---  --- |\n| Internet connection 50 mbps or faster, cable/dsl | $22.19 HK$173.88 | $35.10 SGD45.09 | +58.2% |\n| 1-Bedroom apartment in downtown area | $2,349.29 HK$18,409.13 | $3,116.78 SGD4,003.51 | +32.7% |\n| 1-Bedroom apartment outside city center | $1,688.04 HK$13,227.54 | $2,276.91 SGD2,924.69 | +34.9% |\n| Utilities for two (700 sq 