2026-06-18 19:53:31,776 - [_base_client] - [openai._base_client]: DEBUG - Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/chat/completions', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-69263092-6685-40f6-a8d6-4aa02e8a68c2', 'security': {'bearer_auth': True}, 'content': None, 'json_data': {'messages': [{'content': 'You are an expert research information synthesis agent. You summarize/answer retrieved research information into the most suscinct text possible, but without any extreme terseness that would lose any points, facts, or key information from the provided text you are asked to summarize.', 'role': 'system'}, {'content': "The following text chunks have been retrieved via web search from the reserach query:\n housing rent Singapore Hong Kong expats 2024\nSummarize the results, weighing importance by the relevancy score given, of the query (or provide an answer if the query is a question) with the retrieved results:\n\nResult number 0, relevance score: 0.5863576\n### Coliving Spaces\n\nIf you want to skip the hassle of setting up utilities, buying furniture, or signing a strict two-year lease, coliving is a fantastic option. It allows you to rent a private room (or studio) in a fully furnished, shared apartment with flexible terms, making it ideal for newcomers looking to make friends and settle in quickly.\n\nWhen it comes to award-winning co-living in Singapore, Cove sets the standard. Having snagged the Agoda Gold Circle (2023–2024) and top design honors, they combine style with substance. Their beautifully curated homes in key neighborhoods offer the kind of flexible, community-focused living that perfectly matches the city’s vibrant pace.\n\n### HBD Apartments [...] Update 2024/2025: The Singapore rental market has cooled significantly in the rental market. While prices will never go back to their pre-covid lows, they have come down at least 5-10% from the peak. The market is back to being a renters market and you should negotiate at a minimum 5-10% off the asking price when you see apartments.\n\n## Different Types of apartments in Singapore\n\nTo find your perfect apartment, there’s many things you need to consider. Before I delve into the details, I will go over some key criteria and differences in Germany when it comes to apartment hunting.\n\n### Condominium Buildings [...] This is the final step and at this point, you’ll need to send the rest of the deposit money to the landlord and your lease will finally be official! You’ll also need to send through your first month of rent up front even if your lease doesn’t start until later down the road.\n\n### How much money to pay up front\n\nRenting an apartment in Singapore will incur you a lot of upfront costs. If you’re signing a two year lease, you will pay for two months of security deposit, and the first month of rent upfront. If you’re apartment is $5,000 a month, you can expect to pay\n\n $5000 \\ 2 = $10,000 – Security Deposit\n $5,000 – First month of rent\n $15,000 – upfront cost\n\nResult number 1, relevance score: 0.54594\nFor expats with larger families or anyone craving extra space and privacy, landed properties offer a wonderful lifestyle with generous gardens, room for outdoor activities, and peaceful surroundings. \n\nLiving in a detached bungalow in a central location means enjoying plenty of space and comfort, with monthly rents typically ranging from S$18,000 to 28,000 (US$13,000–20,200). A 4-bedroom bungalow is usually available for around S$15,000 to 27,500 (US$10,800–19,900). Semi-detached and terraced houses offer a cosy alternative, renting for approximately S$8,000 to 13,000 (US$5,700–9,800) per month.\n\nPopular neighbourhoods like Serangoon Gardens, Bukit Timah, and Holland Village attract many expat families thanks to their excellent international schools and family-friendly vibe. [...] ##### Private Housing (Condominiums / Private Apartments)\n\nThis Bali-inspired condominium blends wabi-sabi aesthetics with modern design in a beautifully restored space. Photo: Stacked Homes\n\nCondos are a top pick among expats in Singapore, thanks to added security, pools, gyms, tennis courts and even function rooms.\n\nPopular spots include buzzing areas like Orchard and Bukit Timah, quieter central neighbourhoods like River Valley and Newton, and scenic waterfront enclaves such as Tanjong Rhu and East Coast. [...] ##### 2\n\n##### Make an Offer with a Letter of Intent (LOI)\n\nOnce you’ve found the one, express interest by submitting an LOI along with a good faith deposit (typically one month’s rent). While not legally binding, this shows serious intent and secures the property while final terms are negotiated. \n\nThe LOI often acts as a draft for the Tenancy Agreement (TA). You may skip the LOI if both parties are ready to proceed directly to the TA. \n\nFor expats: Be sure to include a Diplomatic or Repatriate Clause, allowing you to terminate the lease early if you’re transferred or leave Singapore. This usually applies after the first year and requires two months’ notice.\n\nResult number 2, relevance score: 0.5310884\n### Property and Rent Costs\n\nApartment prices in city centers are comparable ($25,175/m² HK vs $23,965/m² SG), but Singapore suburbs are far cheaper ($7,918/m² vs $16,126/m²)( Mortgage rates tilt to Singapore (2.84% vs 3.8% for 20 years)( For expats, Singapore's HDB flats offer subsidized stability (e.g., 4-room units ~S$500K via HDB resale portal), while Hong Kong's micro-flats average HK$10M for 300 sq ft.\n\nHomejourney's currency converter supports HKD-SGD seamlessly, helping investors compare real-time costs safely.\n\n## Property Markets: Investment Potential in Hong Kong vs Singapore [...] Singapore's real estate shines for stability, with URA reporting Q1 2026 private home prices up 2.1% YoY amid cooling measures like ABSD (Additional Buyer's Stamp Duty up to 60% for foreigners). Rental yields average 3.5-4% in OCR (Outside Central Region) vs Hong Kong's 2.5-3% amid high vacancy( Why choose Singapore? Transparent regulations, no capital gains tax, and Homejourney's verified Projects Directory for launches like The Florence Residences (Serangoon, yields ~4%).\n\n### Rental Yields and Buyer Tips\n\n| Aspect | Hong Kong | Singapore | Winner |\n ---  --- |\n| Rental Yield (City Center) | 2.8% | 3.8% | Singapore |\n| Foreign Ownership Ease | Restricted | Allowed w/ ABSD | Singapore |\n| Price Growth 2025-26 | 1.5% | 4.2% (URA) | Singapore | [...] For investors, Singapore's SSR (Seller's Stamp Duty) protects against flipping, ensuring long-term value. Actionable step: Use Homejourney's Property Search to filter OCR condos under S$2M with 4%+ yields. Link to Bank Rates for latest mortgage rates (e.g., DBS 2.8% fixed).\n\n### Insider Investment Advice\n\nAs a Singapore real estate expert, I've seen Hong Kong investors pivot to Singapore for post-2024 China tensions. Target districts like Punggol (20-min MRT to CBD) for family homes (~S$1.2M 4-bed). Homejourney verifies all listings for safety, unlike unvetted sources.\n\n## Lifestyle and Daily Living: Hong Kong vs Singapore\n\nResult number 3, relevance score: 0.51618147\n## Expat Guide to Renting Homes in Hong Kong and Seoul\n\nExplore expat-friendly rental homes in Hong Kong and Seoul. Learn key tips, legal insights, and personal experiences to simplify your housing search abroad.\n\nBy Weave Living, Aug 27, 2025blog post image\n\nSingapore\n\n## Why I Chose Serviced Apartments for Long-Term Stays in Singapore & Seoul\n\nDiscover the benefits of serviced apartments for long-term stays in Singapore and Seoul. Flexible, secure, and hassle-free living for expats and travelers.\n\nWeave Living promotion image\n\nSingapore\n\n## Why I Chose Serviced Apartments for Long-Term Stays in Singapore & Seoul\n\nDiscover the benefits of serviced apartments for long-term stays in Singapore and Seoul. Flexible, secure, and hassle-free living for expats and travelers. [...] Discover why East Coast Singapore is ideal for long-term renters: great connectivity, seaside living, vibrant food culture, and a welcoming community.\n\nWeave Living promotion image\n\nSingapore\n\n## Why East Coast Singapore is Perfect for Long-Term Renters\n\nDiscover why East Coast Singapore is ideal for long-term renters: great connectivity, seaside living, vibrant food culture, and a welcoming community.\n\nBy Weave Living, Sep 04, 2025blog post image\n\nHong Kong\n\n## Expat Guide to Renting Homes in Hong Kong and Seoul\n\nExplore expat-friendly rental homes in Hong Kong and Seoul. Learn key tips, legal insights, and personal experiences to simplify your housing search abroad.\n\nWeave Living promotion image\n\nHong Kong\n\n## Expat Guide to Renting Homes in Hong Kong and Seoul\n\nResult number 4, relevance score: 0.46060488\nIan on Jun 24, 2024:\n\nFor short term experience, yes. $2.5k USD is more than enough with accommodation settled. For long term no unless you intend to be a bartender for life.   \n   \n Varun - if you are frugal you can rent a single room which goes for about $1.2k SGD. 1 bedroom apartments from $2.5k onwards depending on your appetite. Otherwise more than enough.\n\nAnonymous Bartender on Apr 17, 2024:\n\nHello, I am 25, male, I’ve been offered a bartender job in Singapore, they will give me a room in hotel to stay. I’ll eat there, I neither smoke nor drink alcohol. They pay will be around 2.5k usd. Since I won’t have any expenses, I think it will be enough for me to live there. I wonder if you suggest me to accept the offer. Are there any cons of living in Singapore?\n\nVarun on Mar 28, 2024: [...] Varun on Mar 28, 2024:\n\nI have been offered SGD$9892 per month pre tax as a salary. Is this enough for a single man living and working in Singapore?\n\nAnonymous on Mar 11, 2024:\n\nindeed life is good here (referring to the comment below) but the cost of life has increased dramatically. it used to cost me less than SGD20 to get to the airport, now it is about SGD30. You cannot get a flat under SGD3,000 - or you may live in the north of the island, where it would take forever to get to town and work. Since late 2021, the rent went crazy - most people had their rent increased by 75% or more (in our case 105%), for many different reasons. if you don't have enough money for rent and school tuition, life will be tough in SG.\n\nAnonymous on Feb 04, 2024: [...] alvin11 on Jul 15, 2024:\n\nIf you live in the normal apartment's single room (commonly known as HDB - the price range from SGD600 to 1200 depending on area).   \n   \n Monthly food expenses at the hawker centre (food court) will be roughly (SGD500 to 1000 depending on area).   \n   \n Transportation wise is pretty low (SGD50~150 depending on your distance/travel frequency).   \n   \n In average monthly expenses will be roughly SGD1500-2000 at non central area, and roughly SGD2500-no limit at CBD.\n\nIan on Jun 24, 2024:\n\n", 'role': 'user'}], 'model': 'MiniMaxAI/MiniMax-M2.7', 'max_tokens': 8192, 'stream': True}}
