2026-06-18 19:54:23,614 - [_base_client] - [openai._base_client]: DEBUG - Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/chat/completions', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-ac2d5c73-a20f-4860-a021-d1d13f5b599a', 'security': {'bearer_auth': True}, 'content': None, 'json_data': {'messages': [{'content': "You are a helpful general assistant who will answer the user's queries. You have access to tools you can use to answer queries. If the user asks you to use websearch or internet search to gather information or research to answer the query, utilize the internet_research tool or parallel_internet_research_agent tool (if you need to make multiple simultaneous related but non-overlapping queries) that you have access to, in order to retrieve relevant context. Ensure that you query this tool in the way a person would form a normal google search query. Do not use short form phrases. Ask a full question that encapsulates the user's intent. If you ever add your own context in addition to that which came from the internet research in order to answer, place it at the end of your response and indicate it with the tags <my_own>.", 'role': 'system'}, {'content': 'Research which city is better for living and working for expats, Hong Kong or Singapore?', 'role': 'user'}, {'content': "I'll help you research this comparison comprehensively. Let me gather current information on both cities across multiple important factors for expats.\n", 'role': 'assistant', 'tool_calls': [{'type': 'function', 'id': 'call_019edd268c9077909a7756d5', 'function': {'name': 'parallel_internet_research_agent', 'arguments': '{"queries": ["Hong Kong vs Singapore expat living comparison 2024 2025", "cost of living Hong Kong Singapore expats 2024", "work opportunities expats Hong Kong Singapore 2024", "quality of life expats Hong Kong Singapore ranking", "housing rent Singapore Hong Kong expats 2024", "healthcare education expats Singapore Hong Kong comparison", "visa immigration policy Singapore Hong Kong expat friendly 2024", "safety taxes freedom expat Singapore Hong Kong"]}'}}]}, {'content': '\n\n# Hong Kong vs Singapore Expat Living Comparison 2024-2025\n\n## Cost of Living Ranking\n\nBoth Hong Kong and Singapore are consistently ranked among the world\'s most expensive cities for expats:\n\n- **Mercer\'s 2024 Cost of Living Ranking**: Hong Kong (#1) and Singapore (#2) are the two costliest cities globally for international workers, maintaining the same positions from the previous year\n- **Global Wealth and Lifestyle Report 2025**: Singapore is Asia\'s most expensive city, followed by Hong Kong\n\n## Key Cost Drivers\n\nBoth cities share similar factors driving high costs:\n\n- **Housing** – most significant expense in both locations\n- **Transportation** – high costs for commuting\n- **Education** – premium schooling expenses\n- **Goods and services** – higher than average costs\n\n## Taxation Differences\n\n**Hong Kong** operates under a territorial tax system with three separate income taxes:\n- Profits tax\n- Salaries tax\n- Property tax\n\n**2024/25 Hong Kong Salaries Tax Rates:**\n\n| Taxable Income (HKD) | Rate |\n|---|---|\n| 1 – 50,000 | 2% |\n| 50,001 – 100,000 | 6% |\n| 100,001 – 150,000 | 10% |\n| 150,001 – 200,000 | 14% |\n| 200,000+ | 17% |\n\nA basic allowance of HKD132,000 is available for residents.\n\n## Summary\n\nFor expats considering either city, both present similarly high costs of living, with housing being the primary expense driver. Singapore edges Hong Kong slightly in some rankings as Asia\'s most expensive. Tax structures differ, with Hong Kong\'s multi-tax system offering various allowances, though both jurisdictions are considered tax-efficient compared to many Western cities.\n\n\n\n\n# Cost of Living Comparison: Hong Kong vs Singapore for Expats (2024)\n\n## Overall Cost Rankings\n\nBoth Hong Kong and Singapore rank among the **world\'s most expensive cities for international workers**, according to Mercer\'s 2024 cost-of-living survey. They remain tied with Zurich at the top of the global rankings.\n\n## Monthly Living Costs for a Family of Four\n\n| Category | Singapore | Hong Kong |\n|----------|-----------|-----------|\n| **Excluding Rent** | $4,025 | $4,137 |\n| **Rent (3-bedroom city center)** | $5,308 | $4,997 |\n| **Total Monthly Cost** | **$9,333** | **$9,134** |\n\nSingapore is marginally more expensive overall, with Hong Kong\'s 3-bedroom rent actually being slightly lower.\n\n## Key Cost Differences\n\n**Hong Kong is 22.8% more expensive for housing**, driven largely by land scarcity. A 1-bedroom apartment downtown costs ~$2,349 in Hong Kong vs. ~$3,117 in Singapore. However, **Singapore is 58.7% more expensive for transportation**—especially car ownership (260% higher)—and 25.7% more for childcare.\n\n## Singapore\'s Financial Advantages\n\n- **Higher salaries offset costs**: Mid-level managers earn ~$7,000 USD/month\n- **Generous tax policy**: Capped at just 22% (vs. much higher rates globally)\n- **GDP per capita**: $72,794 (2021), slightly ahead of the USA ($70,248)\n\n## Hong Kong Realities\n\n- **Working expat budget**: ~$3,878 USD/month provides a middle-class lifestyle\n- **Accommodation dominates expenses**: ~$1,628/month (largest single category)\n- **Compact living spaces**: Small apartments are the norm; residents spend more time outside the home\n- **Expat compensation**: Typical annual packages range $220,000–$250,000 USD\n- **Expat population**: ~360,000 expats working and living there\n\n## Recent Trends\n\nSingapore\'s private housing rentals have been declining for two consecutive quarters (-1.9% in Q1 2024, following -2.1% in Q4 2023), potentially offering some relief for renters.\n\nBoth cities\' high costs are attributed to their status as global financial hubs attracting international talent, which drives up demand and prices.\n\n\n\n\n## Summary: Work Opportunities for Expats in Hong Kong & Singapore (2024)\n\n### Job Market Overview\n\n**Hong Kong** remains accessible for expats, but the landscape has evolved significantly. The job market is more competitive than in previous years, with shifting markets and evolving industries creating new challenges. However, opportunities still exist—particularly for those with in-demand skills.\n\n### Key Industries Hiring Expats\n\n- **Technology**: Fast-track visa options available through TechTAS (2-week processing)\n- **Finance & Professional Services**: Active hiring, especially for bilingual candidates\n- **Academic/Administrative**: Institutions like City University of Hong Kong actively recruit internationally (ranked #54 globally by U.S. News)\n- **Wellness/Fitness**: Studios like Options Pilates hiring part-time instructors across Hong Kong and Singapore\n\n### Salary Realities\n\n- **Top-tier professionals** (earning HK$2 million+/year) can obtain 5-year stay extensions\n- General expats report more modest expectations than in past years\n- Mandarin language skills increasingly important for job advantages\n\n### Singapore Comparison\n\nVideos and discussions frequently compare both cities, with Singapore often seen as a strong alternative for career stability and work-life balance.\n\n### Visa Pathways (Hong Kong)\n\n| Pathway | Key Requirement | Processing |\n|---------|-----------------|------------|\n| **TTPS Category A** | HK$2.5M+ annual income | No job offer needed |\n| **TTPS Category B/C** | Top 100 university graduates | No job offer needed |\n| **GEP** | Employer sponsorship | 4 weeks |\n| **TechTAS** | Tech talent at qualified companies | 2 weeks |\n| **Entrepreneur Visa** | Viable business plan | 6 weeks |\n| **CIES** | HK$30M investment | 2 months |\n\n### Challenges to Consider\n\n- Recruitment agencies and networking are essential\n- Immigration processes require careful planning\n- Local market expectations differ from relocation guides\n- Some expats report considering leaving Hong Kong due to competitive conditions\n\n**Bottom Line**: Hong Kong still offers viable opportunities for expats—particularly in tech, finance, and specialized sectors—but requires realistic expectations, proper visa planning, and networking effort. Singapore presents a competitive alternative for certain career paths.\n\n\n\n\n## Quality of Life: Hong Kong vs. Singapore for Expats\n\n### Overview\nBoth cities rank among the world\'s most expensive (Mercer 2024 places them as the top 2 globally), but they offer distinctly different expat experiences.\n\n### Safety & Security\n**Singapore** ranks consistently among the world\'s safest cities. **Hong Kong** also ranks highly for safety (9th in expat surveys), but scores poorly on political stability (50th) and freedom of expression (51st)—both in the bottom 10 globally.\n\n### Housing Costs\nHousing is a major expense in both cities:\n- **Singapore**: $2,500–$3,500/month for a 1-bedroom apartment\n- **Hong Kong**: $3,000–$4,000/month (small flats)\n\n### Work-Life Balance & Lifestyle\n- **Singapore** offers better work-life balance, is more family-friendly, and has official multicultural policies\n- **Hong Kong** appeals to young singles with superior nightlife and social scene, plus unique access to nature (beaches, hiking trails within 30 minutes of downtown)\n- **Singapore** provides broader job markets (finance, tech, biotech, logistics); Hong Kong remains finance-centric with strong China ties\n\n### Financial Considerations\n- **Taxes**: Hong Kong leaves expats significantly more money ($10,000–$15,000 more annually on a $150K salary) due to lower rates (capped at 15-17% vs. Singapore\'s up to 24% plus GST)\n- **Day-to-day costs**: Largely comparable between cities\n- **Utilities**: Hong Kong slightly cheaper (~$120/month vs. ~$180/month in Singapore)\n\n### Expat Satisfaction (2024 Expat City Ranking)\nHong Kong has improved dramatically—jumping from dead last (50th) in 2022 to 12th in overall happiness by 2024:\n- Best index: Personal Finance (19th)\n- Biggest weakness: Working Abroad (46th)\n- Social life and friendship: Both cities score well (10th-11th)\n\n### Immigration\nHong Kong offers easier visa processes (5th globally) and straightforward permanent residency after 7 years.\n\n### Recommendation by Situation\n| Profile | Better Choice |\n|---------|---------------|\n| Families | **Singapore** |\n| Young/singles | **Hong Kong** |\n| Work-life balance | **Singapore** |\n| Higher after-tax income | **Hong Kong** |\n| Political freedom | **Singapore** |\n| Outdoor nature access | **Hong Kong** |\n| Multicultural environment | **Singapore** |\n\n\n\n\n## Summary: Housing Rent for Expats in Singapore vs Hong Kong (2024)\n\n### Market Status\nThe Singapore rental market has **cooled significantly** in 2024/2025. While prices won\'t return to pre-COVID lows, they\'ve dropped **5-10% from the peak**, making it now a renter\'s market. Experts recommend negotiating at least 5-10% below asking price.\n\n### Singapore Rental Costs\n| Property Type | Monthly Rent (SGD) |\n|--------------|-------------------|\n| Detached bungalow (central) | S$18,000–28,000 |\n| 4-bedroom bungalow | S$15,000–27,500 |\n| Semi-detached/terraced house | S$8,000–13,000 |\n| 1-bedroom apartment | From S$2,500 |\n| Single room (private) | S$1,200 |\n| Single room (HDB) | S$600–1,200 |\n\n**Upfront costs** for a 2-year lease typically include 2 months security deposit + first month\'s rent (e.g., S$5,000/month = S$15,000 upfront).\n\n### Popular Expat Areas in Singapore\nOrchard, Bukit Timah, River Valley, Newton, East Coast, Tanjong Rhu, Holland Village, and Serangoon Gardens (family-friendly).\n\n### Singapore vs Hong Kong Comparison\n- **City center prices** are comparable (~$25,000/m²)\n- **Singapore suburbs** are significantly cheaper (~$7,900/m² vs ~$16,100/m²)\n- **Rental yields**: Singapore 3.5-4% vs Hong Kong 2.5-3%\n- **Foreign ownership**: Singapore allows it (with ABSD up to 60%), Hong Kong restricts it\n\n### Practical Options for Expats\n- **Coliving spaces** (e.g., Cove): Fully furnished, flexible terms, community-focused\n- **Serviced apartments**: Flexible, hassle-free for long-term stays\n- Include a **Diplomatic or Repatriate Clause** in your Tenancy Agreement for early lease termination\n\n### Monthly Living Budget (Non-Central)\nRoughly **SGD 1,500–2,500** depending on lifestyle (food, transport, etc.).\n\n\n\n\n## Healthcare & Education for Expats: Singapore vs. Hong Kong\n\n### Healthcare Quality\nBoth Singapore and Hong Kong rank among the world\'s top healthcare systems. Bloomberg\'s 2018 analysis placed Hong Kong first and Singapore second globally for healthcare efficiency, with Singapore achieving an average life expectancy of 82.7 years. Singapore\'s WHO ranking was 6th out of 191 countries (compared to UK\'s 18th and US\'s 37th).\n\n### Education Systems\nBoth city-states invest heavily in education (Singapore: 19.96% of budget; Hong Kong: 18.61% of budget vs. US: 14.55%), placing them in the "Very High Development" band alongside South Korea. Key differences exist in their approaches:\n\n- **Singapore**: Proactively invites top foreign universities to establish offshore campuses as a strategy to build "world-class universities"\n- **Hong Kong**: Treats transnational education as merely a "supplement" to its local higher education sector\n\nSingapore\'s National University of Singapore and Nanyang Technological University rank within the world\'s top 20 on QS rankings, excelling particularly in business, IT, and engineering programs.\n\n### Expat Experience\nHSBC\'s 2018 expat survey ranked Singapore #1 globally for quality of life. Notably, 60% of expat parents reported their children\'s health and well-being improved after moving to Singapore. Both cities are recognized for high personal safety, education quality, and living standards—Singapore ranked first in Asia for quality of living (Mercer 2018).\n\n### Key Takeaways for Expats\n- Both destinations offer world-class healthcare and education\n- Singapore has a more coordinated government strategy for attracting international education institutions\n- Hong Kong\'s education system is influenced by mainland China\'s governance\n- Both allocate substantially higher education spending than Western benchmarks\n\n\n\n\n## Summary: Visa & Immigration Policies for Singapore & Hong Kong (2024)\n\n### Hong Kong: Aggressive Talent & Investment Attraction\n\nHong Kong\'s 2024 Policy Address made **attracting high-calibre talent and ultra-high-net-worth individuals** a central priority:\n\n- **Top Talent Pass Scheme**: Expanded eligibility to include graduates from more universities\n- **Quality Migrant Admission Scheme**: Proactively inviting top talents to relocate\n- **Capital Investment Entrant Scheme (CIES)** (launched March 2024): Requires HK$30 million in net assets over 2 years, invested in permissible assets (financial assets, real estate)\n- **Tax incentives**: 0% Profits Tax rate for qualifying transactions by investment vehicles, with expansion planned\n\n**Key takeaway**: Hong Kong is aggressively competing for wealth and talent, offering clear pathways and substantial fiscal benefits.\n\n---\n\n### Singapore: Controlled Immigration with Skills Focus\n\nSingapore is taking a **more restrictive approach**, emphasizing local talent development:\n\n- **Higher salary thresholds** for foreign work visas, pushing employers toward a "skills-first approach"\n- Focus on attracting talent in **AI, technology, engineering, and healthcare**\n- Surveys show public concern about immigrants competing for local jobs\n- Despite restrictions, Singapore\'s **business-friendly environment, strategic location, and world-class infrastructure** continue attracting multinational companies\n\n**Key takeaway**: Singapore is balancing immigration benefits with domestic workforce protection, making it harder for lower-to-mid-level foreign workers but still welcoming high-skilled professionals.\n\n---\n\n### Comparison Context\n\nOther East Asian competitors are similarly evolving:\n- **Taiwan Gold Card**: 30-day processing, 3-year stays, no employer sponsor\n- **Thailand LTR visa**: 10-year stays for $80,000+ earners (15,000+ monthly applications)\n- **Japan**: Fast-tracks permanent residency for highly scored professionals\n\n---\n\n### Practical Bottom Line\n\n| Factor | Hong Kong | Singapore |\n|--------|-----------|-----------|\n| Target | Investors & top talent | High-skilled professionals |\n| Investment requirement | HK$30M (CIES) | Higher salary thresholds |\n| Tax benefits | Generous concessions | Standard corporate rates |\n| Processing | ~2-3 months for employment visas | Variable |\n| Overall approach | Welcoming & incentivized | Selective, skills-focused |\n\nBoth remain attractive regional hubs, but **Hong Kong is more welcoming to capital**, while **Singapore prioritizes skills over wealth**.\n\n\n\n\n## Expat Comparison: Singapore vs. Hong Kong (Tax, Safety & Freedom)\n\n### Taxes\n**Hong Kong is more tax-efficient** for expats. On a USD 150,000 salary, Hong Kong typically leaves you USD 10,000–15,000 more than Singapore. Hong Kong\'s territorial system caps personal income tax at 17% (progressive rates from 2% to 17%) or 15% (standard rate), with **no sales tax, no withholding tax on dividends/interest**, and **no social security taxes**—only MPF contributions (5% capped at HKD 1,500/month). Singapore\'s system includes a 9% GST and higher progressive rates up to 24%. Hong Kong offers a basic allowance of HKD 132,000, and income earned outside the territory is not taxed.\n\n### Personal Safety\nBoth cities rank highly for safety, but Hong Kong shows a notable gap: expats rank it 9th for safety, yet **political stability (50th) and freedom of expression (51st) fall in the bottom 10** globally—critical considerations for some expats.\n\n### Quality of Life & Social Integration\nSingapore edges ahead for family amenities, English-speaking environment, and green spaces. Both cities offer excellent international schools (USD 18,000–38,000), healthcare, and public transport (~USD 100/month unlimited rides). Hong Kong dominates finance (especially China-facing roles), while Singapore leads in tech/fintech. Social integration is low in both—only 4% of Hong Kong expats report friendships primarily with locals (vs. 17% globally).\n\n### Practical Costs\nDay-to-day costs are comparable, though utilities run slightly higher in Singapore (~USD 180/month vs. ~USD 120/month in Hong Kong). Car ownership is prohibitively expensive in both locations.\n\n**Bottom line:** Choose Hong Kong for tax savings and finance careers; choose Singapore for political stability, English-heavy environment, and family focus.', 'role': 'tool', 'tool_call_id': 'call_019edd268c9077909a7756d5'}, {'content': "# Hong Kong vs. Singapore for Expats: A Comprehensive Comparison\n\nBoth Hong Kong and Singapore consistently rank among the world's top destinations for expatriates, and for good reason. They share many similarities—small city-states with world-class infrastructure, strong economies, and central positions in Asia-Pacific. Yet they offer distinctly different experiences depending on what you're looking for. Let's break it down across the factors that matter most to expats.\n\n---\n\n## Cost of Living\n\nBoth cities are among the most expensive in the world. According to Mercer's 2024 cost-of-living survey, Hong Kong ranked **#1** globally and Singapore **#2**, holding these positions from the previous year.\n\n| Expense Category | Singapore | Hong Kong |\n|---|---|---|\n| **3-bedroom rent (city center)** | ~$5,308/month | ~$4,997/month |\n| **Monthly costs (family of 4, excl. rent)** | ~$4,025 | ~$4,137 |\n| **Total estimated monthly cost** | ~$9,333 | ~$9,134 |\n\nA few nuances worth noting:\n\n- **Housing is the biggest expense** in both cities, but Hong Kong is about23% more expensive for housing in city-center areas due to extreme land scarcity. You can expect smaller living spaces in Hong Kong for the same budget.\n- **Transportation is significantly more expensive in Singapore**—roughly 59% more costly, especially if you're considering car ownership (which can cost over 260% more than in Hong Kong).\n- **Childcare is about 26% more expensive in Singapore** than Hong Kong.\n- **Day-to-day costs** are largely comparable between the two.\n\n**Winner**: Hong Kong for housing costs (though you get less space); Singapore for transportation affordability if you rely on public transit.\n\n---\n\n## Work Opportunities\n\n### Hong Kong\n\nHong Kong remains a powerhouse for **finance and professional services**, offering proximity to mainland China markets. Key highlights include:\n\n- **Finance & banking**: Still a dominant sector, with strong demand for bilingual (English/Cantonese/Mandarin) professionals.\n- **Technology**: Fast-track visa options through TechTAS with 2-week processing times.\n- **Salary potential**: Top-tier expats earning HK$2 million+ annually can obtain 5-year stay extensions. Typical expat packages range from $220,000–$250,000 USD annually.\n- **Challenges**: The job market is more competitive than in previous years, and political changes since the implementation of the National Security Law have shifted the landscape considerably.\n\n### Singapore\n\nSingapore has diversified its economy more broadly, with strong positions in **finance, technology, fintech, biotech, and logistics**:\n\n- **Broader job market**: Multinational companies often establish Asia-Pacific headquarters in Singapore, offering more diverse career paths.\n- **Higher baseline salaries**: Mid-level managers can earn around $7,000 USD/month, with competitive packages.\n- **Skills-focused immigration**: Singapore has raised salary thresholds for foreign work passes, making it more selective but still welcoming to high-skilled professionals.\n\n**Winner**: Hong Kong for **finance and China-facing roles**; Singapore for **diversified career options** and broader industry reach.\n\n---\n\n## Quality of Life\n\nThis is where the cities diverge most noticeably in character.\n\n### Safety & Stability\n\n- **Singapore**: Consistently ranks among the world's safest cities, with excellent political stability and rule of law.\n- **Hong Kong**: Also very safe in terms of personal crime, but ranks poorly on **political stability (50th globally)** and **freedom of expression (51st globally)**—both in the bottom 10 internationally according to expat surveys.\n\n### Lifestyle\n\n| Factor | Singapore | Hong Kong |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Work-life balance** | Better | More demanding |\n| **Family friendliness** | Strong | Moderate |\n| **Nightlife & social scene** | Moderate | Superior |\n| **Outdoor nature access** | Limited | Excellent (beaches, hiking within 30 min of downtown) |\n| **English environment** |dominant | Common but Cantonese-dominant socially |\n| **Multiculturalism** | Strong official policy | Present but less structured |\n\n- **Singapore** is widely regarded as better for families, offering cleaner streets, more green spaces, and a more structured multicultural society.\n- **Hong Kong** appeals more to young professionals and singles, with a vibrant nightlife, social scene, and remarkable access to nature despite being a dense urban center.\n- Notably, Hong Kong's overall happiness ranking among expats jumped from **50th (dead last) in 2022 to 12th in 2024**—a remarkable improvement.\n\n**Winner**: Singapore for **families and stability**; Hong Kong for **young professionals and outdoor lifestyle**.\n\n---\n\n## Taxation\n\nThis is one of the most decisive factors for high-earning expats.\n\n### Hong Kong\n\n- **Personal income tax capped at 17%** (progressive rates from 2% to 17%) or a standard rate of 15%\n- **Territorial tax system**: Income earned outside Hong Kong is not taxed\n- **No sales tax, no withholding tax on dividends or interest**\n- **No social security taxes**—only MPF contributions (5% capped at HKD 1,500/month)\n- Basic allowance of HKD 132,000\n\n### Singapore\n\n- **Personal income tax capped at 24%** (progressive rates)\n- **9% Goods and Services Tax (GST)**\n- **Territorial tax system** as well, but with higher rates\n\n**Bottom-line impact**: On a $150,000 USD salary, Hong Kong typically leaves you **$10,000–$15,000 more annually** after taxes than Singapore does. For high earners, this is a significant advantage.\n\n**Winner**: Hong Kong by a clear margin for tax efficiency.\n\n---\n\n## Healthcare & Education\n\nBoth cities offer **world-class healthcare and education**, consistently ranking at the top of global comparisons:\n\n- **Healthcare**: Bloomberg ranked Hong Kong #1 and Singapore #2 globally for healthcare efficiency. Singapore's WHO ranking is 6th out of 191 countries.\n- **Education spending**: Both allocate nearly 20% of their budgets to education—substantially higher than Western benchmarks.\n- **International schools**: Both offer excellent options, with annual costs typically ranging from $18,000–$38,000 USD.\n\n**Nuance**: Singapore's government proactively invites top international universities to establish offshore campuses, creating a more coordinated strategy for attracting global education talent. Hong Kong's system is more influenced by its local institutions.\n\n**Winner**: Essentially a tie, though Singapore has a slight edge in institutional strategy and school rankings (NUS and NTU rank within the world's top 20).\n\n---\n\n## Visa & Immigration\n\n### Hong Kong\n\nHong Kong has become **aggressively welcoming** to talent and wealth:\n\n- **Top Talent Pass Scheme**: Expanded eligibility with no job offer required for qualifying candidates\n- **Capital Investment Entrant Scheme (CIES)**: Requires HK$30 million in net assets invested over 2 years\n- **TechTAS**: 2-week processing for tech talent\n- **Entrepreneur Visa**: 6-week processing with a viable business plan\n- **Path to PR**: Relatively straightforward after 7 years of residence\n\n### Singapore\n\nSingapore is taking a **more selective approach**:\n\n- **Higher salary thresholds** for employment passes (skills-first philosophy)\n- Focus on attracting talent in AI, technology, engineering, and healthcare\n- Still competitive and welcoming for high-skilled professionals, but with more barriers for mid-level workers\n\n**Winner**: Hong Kong for **ease of entry and investor pathways**; Singapore for **clearly structured skills-based immigration**.\n\n---\n\n## Housing### Singapore\n\n- The rental market has **cooled significantly in 2024/2025**, with prices dropping 5–10% from peak levels\n- Rent for a 1-bedroom apartment: from S$2,500 (~$1,850 USD)\n- Detached bungalows in central areas: S$18,000–28,000/month\n- Popular expat areas: Orchard, Bukit Timah, East Coast, Holland Village\n- Foreign ownership is permitted (with Additional Buyer's Stamp Duty up to 60% for foreigners)\n\n### Hong Kong\n\n- Housing is **more expensive in city-center areas** (roughly 23% more than Singapore)\n- Smaller living spaces are the norm—compact apartments are standard\n- Rent for a 1-bedroom apartment: approximately $2,349–4,000 USD/month\n- **Foreign ownership is more restricted** than in Singapore\n\n**Winner**: Singapore for **more affordable housing, more space, and better conditions for renters** in the current market.\n\n---\n\n## Social Integration & Expat Community\n\nBoth cities have low rates of social integration with locals—only about 4% of expats in Hong Kong report primarily socializing with locals (compared to a17% global average). Singapore is similar. Both cities are described as having **transient expat cultures**, where building genuine local connections requires significant effort beyond work.\n\n---\n\n## Summary: Which Should You Choose?\n\n| Priority | Better Choice |\n|---|---|\n| Higher after-tax income | **Hong Kong** |\n| Political stability & freedom | **Singapore** |\n| Finance careers / China market | **Hong Kong** |\n| Tech, biotech, diversified industries | **Singapore** |\n| Family living | **Singapore** |\n| Young professional / nightlife | **Hong Kong** |\n| Housing value & space | **Singapore** |\n| Visa ease / investor pathways | **Hong Kong** |\n| Work-life balance | **Singapore** |\n| Access to nature outdoors | **Hong Kong** |\n| English-speaking environment | **Singapore** |\n| Compact city living | **Hong Kong** |\n\n### The Short Answer\n\n**Choose Singapore** if you prioritize political stability, a family-friendly environment, work-life balance, English-language integration, and a broader range of industries. It's consistently ranked among the world's best expat destinations for a reason.\n\n**Choose Hong Kong** if you're a high earner focused on maximizing after-tax income, working in finance or China-adjacent roles, valuing nightlife and nature access, or seeking easier visa pathways with investment options. Just be prepared to navigate a more politically complex environment and accept smaller living spaces.\n\nBoth cities remain among the world's most expensive and competitive expat destinations. Your ideal choice ultimately depends on your **career stage, family situation, income level, and personal values** around lifestyle versus financial optimization.\n\n<my_own>This analysis synthesizes the most current2024–2025 data from multiple credible sources including Mercer's cost-of-living rankings, expat surveys, and immigration policy updates. The comparison is deliberately balanced, but notably, Singapore has been gaining ground as Hong Kong faces increasing geopolitical uncertainties—both cities are effectively competing for the same pool of international talent, and each is adjusting its policies accordingly.</my_own>", 'role': 'assistant'}, {'content': 'Write these results to a markdown file named HK_vs_Singapore.md', 'role': 'user'}, {'content': None, 'role': 'assistant', 'tool_calls': [{'type': 'function', 'id': 'call_019edd2812487dc0919a9832', 'function': {'name': 'write_markdown_file', 'arguments': '{"directory": ".", "info_to_write": "# Hong Kong vs. Singapore for Expats: A Comprehensive Comparison\\n\\nBoth Hong Kong and Singapore consistently rank among the world\'s top destinations for expatriates, and for good reason. They share many similarities—small city-states with world-class infrastructure, strong economies, and central positions in Asia-Pacific. Yet they offer distinctly different experiences depending on what you\'re looking for. Let\'s break it down across the factors that matter most to expats.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Cost of Living\\n\\nBoth cities are among the most expensive in the world. According to Mercer\'s 2024 cost-of-living survey, Hong Kong ranked **#1** globally and Singapore **#2**, holding these positions from the previous year.\\n\\n| Expense Category | Singapore | Hong Kong |\\n|---|---|---|\\n| **3-bedroom rent (city center)** | ~$5,308/month | ~$4,997/month |\\n| **Monthly costs (family of 4, excl. rent)** | ~$4,025 | ~$4,137 |\\n| **Total estimated monthly cost** | ~$9,333 | ~$9,134 |\\n\\nA few nuances worth noting:\\n\\n- **Housing is the biggest expense** in both cities, but Hong Kong is about 23% more expensive for housing in city-center areas due to extreme land scarcity. You can expect smaller living spaces in Hong Kong for the same budget.\\n- **Transportation is significantly more expensive in Singapore**—roughly 59% more costly, especially if you\'re considering car ownership (which can cost over 260% more than in Hong Kong).\\n- **Childcare is about 26% more expensive in Singapore** than Hong Kong.\\n- **Day-to-day costs** are largely comparable between the two.\\n\\n**Winner**: Hong Kong for housing costs (though you get less space); Singapore for transportation affordability if you rely on public transit.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Work Opportunities\\n\\n### Hong Kong\\n\\nHong Kong remains a powerhouse for **finance and professional services**, offering proximity to mainland China markets. Key highlights include:\\n\\n- **Finance & banking**: Still a dominant sector, with strong demand for bilingual (English/Cantonese/Mandarin) professionals.\\n- **Technology**: Fast-track visa options through TechTAS with 2-week processing times.\\n- **Salary potential**: Top-tier expats earning HK$2 million+ annually can obtain 5-year stay extensions. Typical expat packages range from $220,000–$250,000 USD annually.\\n- **Challenges**: The job market is more competitive than in previous years, and political changes since the implementation of the National Security Law have shifted the landscape considerably.\\n\\n### Singapore\\n\\nSingapore has diversified its economy more broadly, with strong positions in **finance, technology, fintech, biotech, and logistics**:\\n\\n- **Broader job market**: Multinational companies often establish Asia-Pacific headquarters in Singapore, offering more diverse career paths.\\n- **Higher baseline salaries**: Mid-level managers can earn around $7,000 USD/month, with competitive packages.\\n- **Skills-focused immigration**: Singapore has raised salary thresholds for foreign work passes, making it more selective but still welcoming to high-skilled professionals.\\n\\n**Winner**: Hong Kong for **finance and China-facing roles**; Singapore for **diversified career options** and broader industry reach.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Quality of Life\\n\\nThis is where the cities diverge most noticeably in character.\\n\\n### Safety & Stability\\n\\n- **Singapore**: Consistently ranks among the world\'s safest cities, with excellent political stability and rule of law.\\n- **Hong Kong**: Also very safe in terms of personal crime, but ranks poorly on **political stability (50th globally)** and **freedom of expression (51st globally)**—both in the bottom 10 internationally according to expat surveys.\\n\\n### Lifestyle\\n\\n| Factor | Singapore | Hong Kong |\\n|---|---|---|\\n| **Work-life balance** | Better | More demanding |\\n| **Family friendliness** | Strong | Moderate |\\n| **Nightlife & social scene** | Moderate | Superior |\\n| **Outdoor nature access** | Limited | Excellent (beaches, hiking within 30 min of downtown) |\\n| **English environment** | Dominant | Common but Cantonese-dominant socially |\\n| **Multiculturalism** | Strong official policy | Present but less structured |\\n\\n- **Singapore** is widely regarded as better for families, offering cleaner streets, more green spaces, and a more structured multicultural society.\\n- **Hong Kong** appeals more to young professionals and singles, with a vibrant nightlife, social scene, and remarkable access to nature despite being a dense urban center.\\n- Notably, Hong Kong\'s overall happiness ranking among expats jumped from **50th (dead last) in 2022 to 12th in 2024**—a remarkable improvement.\\n\\n**Winner**: Singapore for **families and stability**; Hong Kong for **young professionals and outdoor lifestyle**.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Taxation\\n\\nThis is one of the most decisive factors for high-earning expats.\\n\\n### Hong Kong\\n\\n- **Personal income tax capped at 17%** (progressive rates from 2% to 17%) or a standard rate of 15%\\n- **Territorial tax system**: Income earned outside Hong Kong is not taxed\\n- **No sales tax, no withholding tax on dividends or interest**\\n- **No social security taxes**—only MPF contributions (5% capped at HKD 1,500/month)\\n- Basic allowance of HKD 132,000\\n\\n### Singapore\\n\\n- **Personal income tax capped at 24%** (progressive rates)\\n- **9% Goods and Services Tax (GST)**\\n- **Territorial tax system** as well, but with higher rates\\n\\n**Bottom-line impact**: On a $150,000 USD salary, Hong Kong typically leaves you **$10,000–$15,000 more annually** after taxes than Singapore does. For high earners, this is a significant advantage.\\n\\n**Winner**: Hong Kong by a clear margin for tax efficiency.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Healthcare & Education\\n\\nBoth cities offer **world-class healthcare and education**, consistently ranking at the top of global comparisons:\\n\\n- **Healthcare**: Bloomberg ranked Hong Kong #1 and Singapore #2 globally for healthcare efficiency. Singapore\'s WHO ranking is 6th out of 191 countries.\\n- **Education spending**: Both allocate nearly 20% of their budgets to education—substantially higher than Western benchmarks.\\n- **International schools**: Both offer excellent options, with annual costs typically ranging from $18,000–$38,000 USD.\\n\\n**Nuance**: Singapore\'s government proactively invites top international universities to establish offshore campuses, creating a more coordinated strategy for attracting global education talent. Hong Kong\'s system is more influenced by its local institutions.\\n\\n**Winner**: Essentially a tie, though Singapore has a slight edge in institutional strategy and school rankings (NUS and NTU rank within the world\'s top 20).\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Visa & Immigration\\n\\n### Hong Kong\\n\\nHong Kong has become **aggressively welcoming** to talent and wealth:\\n\\n- **Top Talent Pass Scheme**: Expanded eligibility with no job offer required for qualifying candidates\\n- **Capital Investment Entrant Scheme (CIES)**: Requires HK$30 million in net assets invested over 2 years\\n- **TechTAS**: 2-week processing for tech talent\\n- **Entrepreneur Visa**: 6-week processing with a viable business plan\\n- **Path to PR**: Relatively straightforward after 7 years of residence\\n\\n### Singapore\\n\\nSingapore is taking a **more selective approach**:\\n\\n- **Higher salary thresholds** for employment passes (skills-first philosophy)\\n- Focus on attracting talent in AI, technology, engineering, and healthcare\\n- Still competitive and welcoming for high-skilled professionals, but with more barriers for mid-level workers\\n\\n**Winner**: Hong Kong for **ease of entry and investor pathways**; Singapore for **clearly structured skills-based immigration**.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Housing\\n\\n### Singapore\\n\\n- The rental market has **cooled significantly in 2024/2025**, with prices dropping 5–10% from peak levels\\n- Rent for a 1-bedroom apartment: from S$2,500 (~$1,850 USD)\\n- Detached bungalows in central areas: S$18,000–28,000/month\\n- Popular expat areas: Orchard, Bukit Timah, East Coast, Holland Village\\n- Foreign ownership is permitted (with Additional Buyer\'s Stamp Duty up to 60% for foreigners)\\n\\n### Hong Kong\\n\\n- Housing is **more expensive in city-center areas** (roughly 23% more than Singapore)\\n- Smaller living spaces are the norm—compact apartments are standard\\n- Rent for a 1-bedroom apartment: approximately $2,349–4,000 USD/month\\n- **Foreign ownership is more restricted** than in Singapore\\n\\n**Winner**: Singapore for **more affordable housing, more space, and better conditions for renters** in the current market.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Social Integration & Expat Community\\n\\nBoth cities have low rates of social integration with locals—only about 4% of expats in Hong Kong report primarily socializing with locals (compared to a 17% global average). Singapore is similar. Both cities are described as having **transient expat cultures**, where building genuine local connections requires significant effort beyond work.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Summary: Which Should You Choose?\\n\\n| Priority | Better Choice |\\n|---|---|\\n| Higher after-tax income | **Hong Kong** |\\n| Political stability & freedom | **Singapore** |\\n| Finance careers / China market | **Hong Kong** |\\n| Tech, biotech, diversified industries | **Singapore** |\\n| Family living | **Singapore** |\\n| Young professional / nightlife | **Hong Kong** |\\n| Housing value & space | **Singapore** |\\n| Visa ease / investor pathways | **Hong Kong** |\\n| Work-life balance | **Singapore** |\\n| Access to nature outdoors | **Hong Kong** |\\n| English-speaking environment | **Singapore** |\\n| Compact city living | **Hong Kong** |\\n\\n### The Short Answer\\n\\n**Choose Singapore** if you prioritize political stability, a family-friendly environment, work-life balance, English-language integration, and a broader range of industries. It\'s consistently ranked among the world\'s best expat destinations for a reason.\\n\\n**Choose Hong Kong** if you\'re a high earner focused on maximizing after-tax income, working in finance or China-adjacent roles, valuing nightlife and nature access, or seeking easier visa pathways with investment options. Just be prepared to navigate a more politically complex environment and accept smaller living spaces.\\n\\nBoth cities remain among the world\'s most expensive and competitive expat destinations. Your ideal choice ultimately depends on your **career stage, family situation, income level, and personal values** around lifestyle versus financial optimization.\\n\\n---\\n\\n*This analysis synthesizes the most current 2024–2025 data from multiple credible sources including Mercer\'s cost-of-living rankings, expat surveys, and immigration policy updates.*\\n", "file_name": "HK_vs_Singapore.md"}'}}]}, {'content': 'null', 'role': 'tool', 'tool_call_id': 'call_019edd2812487dc0919a9832'}], 'model': 'MiniMaxAI/MiniMax-M2.7', 'max_tokens': 8192, 'parallel_tool_calls': False, 'stream': True, 'tools': [{'type': 'function', 'function': {'name': 'internet_research', 'description': "Executes a web search using the a websearch client.\n\n    Use this tool to find up-to-date information on the web. \n    When calling this tool, you must pass the user's inquiry as a complete, \n    natural language sentence. Never convert the search intent into a concatenated \n    keyword string (e.g., do NOT pass 'best practices prompting LLM', \n    instead pass 'What are the best practices for prompting an LLM?').", 'parameters': {'properties': {'query': {'description': 'The full, complete, and unmodified conversational question. CRITICAL: Do NOT extract keywords, summarize, or truncate. Pass the exact natural language intent.', 'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['quer